 l’indépendance) / Scarce does a new face shine forth from the old year’s course (Ode to Independence) -- tDans ton variable contour (Ode à l’indépendance) Why ply you your fickle ministry? (Ode to Independence) -- tVoyez ce vieux colon / See that old planter -- tDu Sud et de l’Ouest / From South and West -- tÀ travers les sillons par la foudre tracés / About the lightning-flaring furrows -- tSalut, lointains climats! (Ode sur l’indépendance d’Haïti) / Hail, distant climes! (Ode on Haitian Independence) -- tQuel est ce Roi, dont la bonté? / What King, this, he whose weal outspread? -- tLe monde a salué tes fils (Hymne à l’indépendance) / The world has hailed your sons (Hymn to Independence) -- tAu loin, qui brille à nos yeux étonnés? / What looms there, shining afar before our startled eyes? -- tLe Lis un jour dit au Palmier (Le Lis et le Palmier) / One day, Lily to Palm says (The Lily and the Palm) -- tMuse, à des chants nouveaux j’ai consacré ma lyre (L’Haïtiade, Chant premier) / O Muse, now to new songs I tune my lyre (The Haitiade, Canto 1) -- tLes Betjouanes / The Bechouans -- tQuand le ciel se dorait d’un beau soleil couchant (Pétion) / When the sky donned the setting sun’s fine golds (Pétion) -- tHélas! je me souviens de ce jour (Mila) / Oh! I recall that day (Mila) -- tC’est là qu’il est tombé (Le Pont rouge) / There did he fall (The Pont-Rouge) -- tDessalines!... À ce nom, amis, découvrons-nous! / Dessalines!... At that name, doff hats, my friends! -- tQu’ils sont délicieux tes jours de liberté! (Au Génie de la patrie) / Oh, the delight of your days freedom-spent! (To the Spirit of the Fatherland) -- tMon père, j’aime à voir ces champs et leurs coteaux / Father dear, how I love to cast my glance over these hills and fields -- tPersécutés sur ce rivage / Harried, we stand upon this shore -- tDu Dieu des opprimés célébrons la puissance! / All praise his power, the God of the oppressed! -- tJe suis fier de le dire, ô négresse, je t’aime (La Négresse) / Proudly I say, “I love you,” negress mine (The Negress) -- tFrères, nous avons tous brisé le joug infâme (Aux Haïtiens) / Brothers all, we have now that foul yoke broken (To the Haitians) -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the nineteenth century, Haiti became the first and only modern country born from a slave revolt. During the first decades of Haitian independence, a wealth of original poetry was created by the inhabitants of the former French Caribbean island colony and published in Haitian newspapers. These deeply felt poems celebrated the legitimacy of the new nation and the value of the authors’ African origins while revealing a common mission shared by all Haitians in the young republic: freedom from oppressors and equality for all. This powerfully moving collection of Haitian verse written between 1804 and the late 1840s sheds a much-needed light on an important and often neglected period in Haiti’s literary history. Editors Doris Kadish and Deborah Jenson have gathered together poetry that has remained largely unknown and difficult to access since its original publication two centuries ago. Featuring superb translations from the original French by Norman Shapiro and a foreword by the Haitian-born novelist Edwidge Danticat, this essential volume stands as a monument to a turning point in Haitian and world history and makes a significant corpus of poetry accessible to a wide audience for the first time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHaitian poetryvTranslations into English. 7aPOETRY / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aArdouin, Coriolan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanlatte, Juste, econtributor.4ctb4http